The paper deals with questions related to partitioning and bisecting masses in $\mathbb{R}^d$, which are topics in computational geometry (cs.CG) and discrete mathematics (cs.DS). The use of topological methods suggests that the paper may also be relevant to algebraic topology (math.AT) and geometric topology (math.GT). The study of equipartitions and bisecting with cones and wedges involves concepts from geometry and topology, which further supports the relevance of these sub-categories.
